If a temporal entity T1 is after another temporal entity T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2. Temporal entities can either be a xsd:dateTime (time:TimeInstance) or a ids:TemporalEntity ([ ids:begin {xsd:dateTime}; ids:end {xsd:dateTime} ]).
Less-than operator. Can be used for numeric (2 idsc:LT 5) or qualitative comparisons (idsc:INTEGRITY_PROTECTION_NONE idsc:LT idsc:INTEGRITY_VERIFICATION_REMOTE).

Remote target for an action or information provider (PIP). Must be used together with idsc:eq or idsc:in operators. RightOperand must be a xsd:anyUri which should point to an actually deployed endpoint. An example is a refinment of idsc:NOTIFY where idsc:REMOTE points to a Clearing House.
Less-than-or-equals operator. Can be used for numeric (2 idsc:LTEQ 5) or qualitative comparisons (idsc:INTEGRITY_PROTECTION_NONE idsc:LTEQ idsc:INTEGRITY_VERIFICATION_REMOTE).
Specifies that a given time point is inside a given ids:TemporalEntity. Recommended pattern for temporal intervals is [ ids:begin {xsd:dateTime}; ids:end {xsd:dateTime} ].

Element-of operator, also stating that a instance is in the boundaries of a certain range or area. Allowed RightOperands are RDF collections('(A B C)'), defined areas (http://dbpedia.org/resource/Europe), or ids:SpatialEntity.

Equals operator. Actual semantic depends on the related LeftOperand. For instance, idsc:NOW (time:TimeInstance) requires a comparison of temporal instances while idsc:count demands a numeric comparison.
If a user has a specific role required for accessing a resource. Must be used together with a RightOperand of type xsd:anyUri which should point to an accessible endpoint providing this information.
Greater-than-or-equals operator. Can be used for numeric (5 idsc:GTEQ 2) or qualitative comparisons (idsc:INTEGRITY_VERIFICATION_REMOTE idsc:gteq idsc:INTEGRITY_PROTECTION_NONE).

If a temporal entity T1 is before another temporal entity T2, then the ending of T1 is before the end of T2. Temporal entities can either be a xsd:dateTime (time:TimeInstance) or a ids:TemporalEntity ([ ids:begin {xsd:dateTime}; ids:end {xsd:dateTime} ]).
Greater-than operator. Can be used for numeric (5 idsc:GT 2) or qualitative comparisons (idsc:INTEGRITY_VERIFICATION_REMOTE idsc:GT idsc:INTEGRITY_PROTECTION_NONE).

Separate certificates for IDS identification and transport encryption opens an attack vector for relay attacks. In order to prevent these attacks, a binding of this transport certificates to the connector is required. The inclusion of SHA256 fingerprints of currently valid transport certificates, mainly into the DAT, enables the client to relate the transport layer security with the IDS interactions.

explanation.value:
Definition of a Resource Endpoint is by purpose split into an address part (path, topic etc.)
and host information used to augment and resolve the address. Such the overall address space
is self-contained and may move across hosts. Further, changes of either component (address vs. host)
do not affect the other.
